\begin{abstract}
The combination of deep exposures and high resolution offered by
telescopes in space allows the detection of lensing over a wide range
of source redshifts and lens masses. As an example, we model a lens
candidate found in the southern Hubble Deep Field. The system consists
of a source galaxy lensed into an arc, $0\farcs9$ from an elliptical
galaxy. The photometric redshift of 0.6 for the lens galaxy implies a
mass-to-light ratio of 15 in solar units, out to three effective
radii. This lens system may be a preview of the large number of lensed
high-redshift galaxies that will be detected with the Next Generation
